    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "No, I actually _love_ the visual sytling on stderr.  It's something I've wanted for _years_ on terminals, so I'm glad we can finally have it!! I was just wondering if it would be better to change the background shade from white to light red for stderr instead of changing the text color, as people may try to color the output themselves (like sphinx messages do).  It seems a bit safer to mess around with the text background than to override the text color.\n\nOnly one question: is it possible to reduce the amount of vertical padding between separate divs when we switch? Try this:\n\n<pre>\nimport sys\nfor i in range(8):\n    print i\n    print >> sys.stderr, i\n    sys.stdout.flush()\n    sys.stderr.flush()\n</pre>\n\n\nit seems there's too much vertical whitespace between divs.\n\nBut this is otherwise awesome!\n"
  },
