    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I don't really like the aesthetic of coloring the stdout/stderr backgrounds.  If anything, we want to distinguish output as a whole from input, and it is somewhat unfortunate that `Out[]:` has a (super useful) logical meaning that prevents us using it to denote all output for a cell, because that's what I would really want from a UI standpoint.  I've played with various styles, giving various elements borders and backgrounds, and I really don't like any of them yet.  The lightest one that I dislike least so far, is a simple thin/light line separating the `In:` prompt, a la:\n\n<img src=https://img.skitch.com/20111008-dexp7drus7ss7t5n8smicnw7wp.png/>\n\nIt seems like what we really want is some indicator distinguishing output in general from input in general, rather than extra delineation of stream output from everything else.  In Terminal IPython, this is provided by the continuation prompts, and the In-prompt thin-border seems the most browser-appropriate way to do that.  I also played with styling the code area with a background itself, but it didn't feel right.\n"
  },
